VALUES ('63503b55-6357-4441-8533-80cd1bd02332', 'Which choice best describes the relationship between the text''s opening and its conclusion?', 'Engineers prototyping turbine 100231 demonstrated that angled blades harvest more energy from low wind speeds, a design inspired by the shape of humpback whale fins. Standard flat blades stall when air flow separates early, wasting kinetic energy that never reaches the generator. The prototype''s tubercle-like ridges delay separation, maintaining lift across a wider range of wind speeds common in residential installations. Wind-tunnel tests documented a twelve-percent gain at moderate speeds without increasing noise above local ordinance limits. The engineers note that biomimicry here is not decorative; it directly addresses a performance bottleneck that limits small-scale renewable adoption. However, empirical work since then has challenged the absolute applicability of the view introduced at the outset. The passage moves from biological observation to mechanical testing to a', 'passage', '[{"id":"A","text":"It treats the author''s caution as evidence of personal indecision rather than as a deliberate rhetorical strategy the structure enacts throughout the paragraph in sum in context.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Partial Scope] [Narrative Speculation] Imports unsupported assumptions about author motivation or future plans."},{"id":"B","text":"It presents the counter-perspective as appearing before the consensus view, reversing the actual order of ideas in the text from established model to challenge in context.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Narrative Speculation] [Structural Inversion] Reverses the actual sequence of ideas the passage develops."},{"id":"C","text":"It contrasts an earlier consensus with newer findings, reconciles partial agreement with dispute, and qualifies the scope of the conclusion as written here throughout overall in sum.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct (C). Correct (C). This choice matches the passage''s rhetorical architecture from framework through evidence to qualified implications."},{"id":"D","text":"It accurately describes the concession in sentence two but ignores how the passage integrates that concession into a broader qualified defense in the closing sentences here.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Structural Inversion] [Partial Scope] Describes only part of the passage, ignoring its overall trajectory."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Step 1 — Identify the passage organization
