VALUES ('9db8f028-10bc-463c-9970-0010efb4c2cb', 'Which choice best describes the relationship between the text''s opening and its conclusion?', 'Marine biologists studying reef ecosystem 100241 found that parrotfish grazing limits algae growth, allowing coral larvae to settle on bare rock. Without sustained grazing, fast-growing algae can smother reefs within a single season, turning complex habitat into a uniform green mat. The researchers tracked grazing rates across three seasons and compared sites where parrotfish populations had declined after local fishing pressure. At those sites, coral recruitment—the process by which free-floating larvae attach to hard substrate—dropped sharply even when water temperature and salinity remained stable. Still, archival evidence qualifies the sweeping claim, showing that exceptions accumulated across multiple sites. The team argues that protecting herbivorous fish is not merely a conservation aesthetic but a functional requirement for reef recovery after bleaching events. Their follow-up surveys showed that small patches of bare rock reappeared only where grazing intensity returned to historical norms.', 'passage', '[{"id":"A","text":"It contrasts an earlier consensus with newer findings, reconciles partial agreement with dispute, and qualifies the scope of the conclusion throughout overall in sum in context.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct (A). Correct (A). This choice matches the passage''s rhetorical architecture from framework through evidence to qualified implications."},{"id":"B","text":"It accurately describes the concession in sentence two but ignores how the passage integrates that concession into a broader qualified defense in the closing sentences overall.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Partial Scope] Describes only part of the passage, ignoring its overall trajectory."},{"id":"C","text":"It treats the author''s caution as evidence of personal indecision rather than as a deliberate rhetorical strategy