VALUES ('98c15817-4128-4ee3-95b0-82fa8b8fae98', 'Which choice best describes the overall structure of the passage?', 'Engineers prototyping turbine 100263 demonstrated that angled blades harvest more energy from low wind speeds, a design inspired by the shape of humpback whale fins. Standard flat blades stall when air flow separates early, wasting kinetic energy that never reaches the generator. However, empirical work since then has challenged the absolute applicability of the view introduced at the outset. The prototype''s tubercle-like ridges delay separation, maintaining lift across a wider range of wind speeds common in residential installations. Wind-tunnel tests documented a twelve-percent gain at moderate speeds without increasing noise above local ordinance limits. The engineers note that biomimicry here is not decorative; it directly addresses a performance bottleneck that limits small-scale renewable adoption. The passage moves from biological observation to mechanical testing to a practical deployment implication. Field monitoring over six months confirmed that the gain persisted under variable', 'passage', '[{"id":"A","text":"It assumes the author dismisses prior scholarship entirely rather than engaging and qualifying specific claims the text explicitly considers in the middle sections as written here.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Partial Scope] [Narrative Speculation] Imports unsupported assumptions about author motivation or future plans."},{"id":"B","text":"It treats the passage as a chronological biography, ignoring the pivot from consensus to challenge that organizes the discussion across the full paragraph here throughout overall.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Narrative Speculation] [Structural Inversion] Reverses the actual sequence of ideas the passage develops."},{"id":"C","text":"It posits an established model, evaluates evidence that complicates it, and qualifies the pragmatic stakes of the revised interpretation throughout over