VALUES ('c2c324f1-214a-418e-8895-0985e35f7a58', 'Which choice best characterizes the text''s rhetorical structure?', 'Psychologists testing memory task 100270 reported that participants who slept eight hours recalled word lists more accurately than those who stayed awake, even when both groups studied equally long. The awake group was kept in a quiet lounge with books and puzzles to prevent napping, yet their recall still lagged behind the sleep group on both immediate and delayed tests. Brain-imaging subsamples showed differences in hippocampal activity during retrieval, aligning with theories that sleep consolidates declarative memories. By contrast, later analysts argued that the initial synthesis overlooked boundary conditions essential to interpretation. The researchers caution that the study measured short lists under lab conditions and may not generalize to complex real-world learning. Still, the controlled comparison isolates sleep as the key variable because study time, list difficulty, and initial exposure were matched. The passage presents sleep as a cognitive process', 'passage', '[{"id":"A","text":"It claims effects are analyzed before causes are defined, inverting the passage''s movement from causal mechanism to documented outcome in the study described here throughout overall in context as written here throughout overall in sum.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Partial Scope] [Structural Inversion] Reverses the actual sequence of ideas the passage develops."},{"id":"B","text":"It establishes a cause-and-effect claim, supplies seasonal field evidence, and acknowledges limitations before drawing implications throughout overall in sum in context as written here throughout overall as written here throughout","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct (B). Correct (B). This choice matches the passage''s rhetorical architecture from framework through evidence to qualified implications."},{"id":"C","text":"It lists technical vocabulary from the opening sentences without showing how those terms support a cumulative argument across the full paragraph from mechanism to outcome overall, as the passage''s own framing here throughout overall in","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Narrative Speculation] [Partial Scope] Describes only part of the passage, ignoring its overall trajectory."},{"id":"D","text":"It predicts that the author will publish a memoir, a motivation the passage never discusses or reasonably implies from its expository structure and academic tone in sum, in a way that matches how the author.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Structural Inversion] [Narrative Speculation] Imports unsupported assumptions about author motivation or future plans."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Step 1 — Identify the passage organization
Focus on {{yellow:retrieval,}} in the passage. The structure item asks you to identify the passage organization before comparing choices.

Step 2 — Match structure to purpose
Compare each option against explicit textual evidence. On hard items, correct answers usually restate the passage faithfully without absolute words the text does not support.

Step 3 — Confirm the description
Choice B is correct: It establishes a cause-and-effect claim, supplies seasonal field evidence, and acknowledges limitations before drawing implications throughout overall in sum in….

Distractor analysis:
- A: [Partial Scope] [Structural Inversion] Reverses the actual sequence of ideas the passage develops.
- C: [Narrative Speculation] [Partial Scope] Describes only part of the passage, ignoring its overall trajectory.
- D: [Structural Inversion] [Narrative Speculation] Imports unsupported assumptions about author motivation or future plans.', NULL, 'Craft and Structure', 'Text Structure and Purpose', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'TSP', NULL, 'hard', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"rw_subtype":"structure","rw_format":"passage_mc","generator":"regenerate-english-fresh.mjs","regen_seed_offset":100000,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
